<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910719-0058</DOCNO><DOCID>910719-0058.</DOCID><HL>   World Markets:   Tokyo Stocks Post Third Fall in Row;   London Shares Soften on Weak Data   ----   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup</HL><DATE>07/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10</SO><MS>BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)</MS><IN>COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)</IN><NS>COMMODITIES MARKET (CMD)STOCK andamp; OTHER MARKET NEWS (STK)</NS><RE>AUSTRALIA (ASA)CANADA (CN)EUROPE (EU)FAR EAST (FE)FRANCE (FR)GERMANY (GE)HONG KONG (HK)JAPAN (JA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)SWITZERLAND (SZ)GREAT BRITAIN (UK)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   Tokyo stocks fell Thursday for the third consecutive day,mostly on concern about the expanding scandal in Japan'ssecurities industry. London shares weakened after economicdata failed to signal a recovery.   In Tokyo, the 225-stock Nikkei index, which lost 314.45points Wednesday, dropped 151.99 to 22908.71. The firstsection's Tokyo Stock Price Index, or Topix, which shed 18.38points Wednesday, was down 8.95 at 1795.37. First-sectionvolume was estimated at 230 million shares, compared with240.6 million shares a day earlier. Declining issuesoutnumbered advancing issues 712-211.</LP><TEXT>   In Tokyo on Friday, the Nikkei rose 58.72 points to closethe morning session at 22967.43.   Buying interest on Thursday was stifled by midday newsthat the Japanese Ministry of Finance had launched aninspection of the Big Four securities companies forcompensatory payments to big clients. The resulting declinein the Nikkei prompted bargain-hunting, mostly of blue chips,led by foreign investors.   In London, statistics on employment, industrialproduction, earnings and bank lending indicated that theBritish economy is still in recession. The FinancialTimes-Stock Exchange 100-share index shed 13.7 points to2547.3. The FT 30-share index declined 9.6 points to 1969.0.Stock prices were also hurt by a weak futures market and bypoor corporate news.   In Frankfurt, the DAX index closed at 1618.33, down 7.18points. Weakness in major world stock markets, softness inGerman bond prices and worries about possible interest-rateincreases also damped buying.   In Madrid, share prices fell sharply on news thegovernment plans to keep a tight rein on monetary policy, inthe wake of failed labor talks. The government had hoped torein in inflation by an agreement linking wages andproductivity.   Among corporate developments, in Tokyo, Mitsubishi HeavyIndustries fell 14 yen, or 1.9%, to 696 yen ($5.08), Komatsudropped 16, or 1.8%, to 861, and Hitachi was unchanged at1,110. In a widening corporate espionage scandal, policeinvestigated Mitsubishi Heavy and a unit of electronics giantHitachi after officials at Toyo Unpanki, a machinery maker,acknowledged they paid for documents allegedly stolen fromKomatsu, the world's second-largest maker of constructionmachinery.   In London, Reed International plummeted 12 pence, or 2.7%,to 435 pence ($7.17). The publishing group predicted adecline in results for the first half ending Oct. 31 from ayear earlier, citing softer markets.   Great Universal Stores Class A shares plunged 31, or 2.4%,to #12.59 ($20.77), dragged down by the market's slide. Theretailer's pretax profit in the year ended March 31 rose 3.4%to #431.3 million ($711.6 million).   British Telecommunications tumbled 12, or 3.2%, to 365.5pence. The telecommunications group said at the annualmeeting that its profit would be eroded if the companyaccepted regulators' latest proposals. The government movedin March to end the company's domination of Britain'stelecommunications market.   In Paris, Societe Nationale Elf Aquitaine jumped 9.9French francs, or 2.9%, to 349.90 francs ($57.57). Thestate-controlled petroleum concern agreed to sell all of itsupstream, or production and distribution, assets in Spain toRepsol, a state-controlled Spanish oil company. The pricewasn't disclosed. In Madrid, Repsol fell 20 pesetas to 2,615pesetas ($23.29).   In Brussels, Gechem closed unchanged at 728 Belgian francs($19.74). The polyurethane foam maker expects a slight lossfor 1991, citing financial charges and amortization of goodwill stemming from a U.S. acquisition last year. Groupconsolidated profit was 1.49 billion Belgian francs ($40.5million).   In Johannesburg, Anglo American Corp. of South Africa rose3.25 rand to 122.50 rand ($42.59). Combined second-quarterprofits of the conglomerate's six gold mines rose 4.3% to393.5 million rand ($136.8 million) from the first quarter.In reporting quarterly results, South African gold mines makecomparisons with the previous quarter rather than theyear-earlier period because swings in revenue, tax andexpenditure tend to obscure the longer-term comparison.                                                                                                          Here are price trends on the world's major stock markets,as calculated by Morgan Stanley Capital InternationalPerspective, Geneva. To make them directly comparable, eachindex is based on the close of 1969 equaling 100. Thepercentage change is since year-end.                                                                                                                                                         % This                               Jul 17    Jul 16     Year                                                                                                          U.S. ....................   354.9     355.2    + 15.6   Britain .................   763.7     762.1    + 19.5   Canada ..................   396.2     394.9    +  8.0   Japan ...................  1025.0    1036.3    +  3.1   France ..................   490.5     489.8    + 15.6   Germany .................   256.3     258.9    + 13.6   Hong Kong ...............  2901.9    2930.1    + 33.6   Switzerland .............   214.5     214.4    + 27.0   Australia ...............   329.4     329.5    + 2